One year ago today, the President signed the #PACTAct into law with @SusanZeier, Heath’s wife Danielle, & their daughter by his side.

The #PACTAct added 23 new medical conditions to the VA’s list of presumptive conditions for toxic exposure. Meaning if a toxic-exposed veteran is diagnosed with one of these illnesses — they will get VA coverage for it. Period.

We brought their ideas together and wrote the #PACTAct to expand health care eligibility for veterans exposed to burn pits & other toxic substances. 

We named the bill after Heath Robinson.
We listened to veterans, we listened to military families, and we worked to find a solution that would provide veterans exposed to toxins the care they were owed.

I pushed the Veterans Affairs Committee to hold a hearing with VA leaders & disease experts. We also brought the committee to Ohio to hear from local veterans & VA employees. 

We did what too often Washington doesn’t do: we listened.
Heath wasn’t alone. Thousands of veterans were getting sick & dying from toxic exposure, but struggled to prove their illnesses were service connected — so their VA claims were denied.

Heath, a two-time Ohio National Guard NCO of the year, had been exposed to football-field-sized toxic burn pits during his service. 

In 2020, he passed away from a rare form of lung cancer.

As we celebrate the anniversary of the #PACTAct becoming law, I wanted to reflect on how we got here.

In 2017, I met @SusanZeier, the mother-in-law of Sergeant First Class Heath Robinson — an Ohioan who served in Iraq.
